## Plan: Add Pagination to GET /users

**Only one file needs to change:** `src/routes.ts`

### Exploration findings
- **Stack:** Node.js + TypeScript + Express, in-memory data store (15 users in `src/data.ts`)
- **Current handler:** Returns the raw `users` array with no envelope
- **Tests:** Already written in `tests/routes.test.ts` — 4 pagination tests define the exact contract

### The change — replace the GET /users handler body

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1);
  const limit = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10);

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

### Why this works for every test case

| Test | Params | Result |
|---|---|---|
| Default | _(none)_ | `page=1, limit=10` → 10 users, `total=15, totalPages=2` |
| Page 2 | `?page=2&limit=10` | `start=10` → 5 users remaining |
| Custom limit | `?limit=5` | `totalPages=ceil(15/5)=3` |
| Out-of-range | `?page=100` | `start=990`, `slice(990,1000)=[]` → empty array, status 200 |

`Array.slice()` returns `[]` naturally when the start index exceeds the array length — no special-casing needed for out-of-range pages.

No other files need to be modified. Run `npm test` to verify all 6 tests pass.
